I remember the first time I drew a face. It looked like this:

{%pic "./imgs/face.png", "a face" %}

I was with my older cousin, sitting on the slope of a hill overlooking my house. It was a late summer afternoon: still warm, with the grass still golden, but slowly turning red, the air smelling like honey and beeswax. He drew first. I followed.

That's how I draw faces now:

{%pic "./imgs/face-now.png", "a face" %}

I also remember the first letter I ever wrote! It looked like this:

{%pic "./imgs/r.png", "an r" %}

I drew it on a wooden plank with a red flat carpenter pencil. The shape of the [lead](https://www.beatsons.co.uk/images/faithfull-carpenters-pencils-red-pack-of-3-sharp-card-p7045-30241_medium.jpg) and the texture of the wood made it hard to draw curves. You had to go in straight lines and press just a little bit so the lead didn't sink into the pulp.

I drew it in the room all of us slept and watched TV. The light was crisp (with the shadows freshly chiseled) and the air smelled of spring and tobacco. My dad wrote first. Then I followed.

This is how I write now:

{%pic "./imgs/hi.png", "a hi" %}

_Hello!_ says the impostor syndrome (nihilism kicks in): I'm none of the things I wanted to be between then and now. I still draw the same face and I still write the same «ر».

{# Impostor syndrome and nihilism kicks in when I don't feel useful. I drew 1000s of faces and this one time I had spent several nights writing the word "love" in the same style 1000s of times to get it right. #}

